<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1929-04-10T13:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1929-04-10T13:00:00-05:00" n="660" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d660">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">312.1722 Sandino/3: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in Honduras</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Summerlin</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Tegucigalpa</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1929-04-10T12:00:00-06:00">April 10,
                                1929—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received 3:32 p.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>35. The Subsecretary for Foreign Affairs has just informed me by
                            direction of the President of the Republic that the Minister of Mexico
                            has requested permission for Sandino to pass unarmed through Honduras on
                            his way to Mexico. Doctor Duron appeared to view the request
                            sympathetically, but stated that no reply has yet been made to the
                            Mexican Minister.</p>
                        <p>Repeated to Managua.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Summerlin</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>